^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|You played the hand well. One important point on this hand is the spade suit. Whenever the opponents have an ^*Bodd^*N number of cards out in one of your suits, the suit will usually break as ^*Bevenly^*N as possible. So, the common example is when you have an 8-card fit, with 5 out for the opponents. The most likely break with 5 cards missing is 3-2. |
PG| ***** 19 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|When you have a 10-card fit (3 missing) the most likely break is 2-1.  And, on this hand, when you have a 6-card fit (as in spades), with 7 out the most likely break is 4-3. That means once Ruth takes the Ace, all Jacquie should need to do is ruff 1 spade to set up the suit.|
PG| ***** 20 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|On the other hand, if the opponents have an ^*Beven^*N number of cards out, they will tend to break ^*Bunevenly^*N. With a 9-card fit (4 out) the suit will break 3-1 more often than 2-2. And with a 7-card fit (6 out) the suit will break 4-2 more often than 3-3.|
PG| ***** 21 ***** |


